<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 10:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I295dd720630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Documentary and Demonstrative Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id7210189682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:17.</label.designator><headtext>Persons</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Exhibiting a person to the jury is proper evidence where relevant[<footnote.reference refid="I7aedfcc074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] and lies within the discretion of the judge.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Georgia courts allow a child to be exhibited to the jury in the following actions: paternity,[<footnote.reference refid="I7aedfcc174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] abandonment,[<footnote.reference refid="I7aedfcc274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] and breach of promise.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7aedfcc374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A person may be exhibited to the jury to show wounds or injury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7aedfcc474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] A plaintiff who had lost both legs in a train wreck was permitted to show the jury that he could walk a little on his knees.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7aee23d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, the Court held it was improper for the prosecution to have the defendant&apos;s girl friend stand during closing arguments and argue to the jury that the girlfriend was clearly available to testify on behalf of the defendant, but had not done so to corroborate the defendant&apos;s story.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7aee23d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7aedfcc074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="0280312591" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="TS" w-pub-number="0134642" ID="I182dd60074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">McCormick on Evidence § 215 (6th ed.)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aedfcc174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1974020524" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000108" ID="I182e4b3174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bastardy proceedings: Propriety of exhibition of child to jury to show family resemblance, or lack of it, on issue of paternity, 55 A.L.R.3d 1087</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aedfcc274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1960123004" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182e995274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hunt v. State, 101 Ga. App. 126, 112 S.E.2d 817 (1960)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1963126130" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182e995574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Burton v. State, 107 Ga. App. 792, 131 S.E.2d 579 (1963)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1979126851" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182e995874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Kelly v. State, 149 Ga. App. 76, 253 S.E.2d 419 (1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1979127153" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182e995b74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Joseph v. State, 149 Ga. App. 296, 254 S.E.2d 383 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aedfcc374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1938106724" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I182f0e8274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Morris v. Stanford, 58 Ga. App. 726, 199 S.E. 773 (1938)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aedfcc474d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1936106248" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I182faac274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wagoner v. State, 52 Ga. App. 379, 183 S.E. 209 (1936)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1950104724" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182faac574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Stembridge v. State, 82 Ga. App. 214, 60 S.E.2d 491 (1950)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1982151848" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182faac874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rollins v. State, 164 Ga. App. 452, 297 S.E.2d 352 (1982)</cite.query> (stab wounds and resultant scars); Annot., <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1959012916" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000107" ID="I182faaca74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">66 A. L. R. 2d 1334</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1988045652" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I182faacd74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Burrell v. State, 186 Ga. App. 48, 366 S.E.2d 385 (1988)</cite.query> (scars).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aee23d074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1909013806" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1830470274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Southern Ry. Co. v. Brock, 132 Ga. 858, 64 S.E. 1083 (1909)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="1975131585" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1830470574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Huff v. State, 135 Ga. App. 134, 217 S.E.2d 187 (1975)</cite.query>, a victim&apos;s wound was properly exhibited to the jury to show the angle at which the bullet entered his body. <eos/><bos/>This was a proper exhibition and not a demonstration.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7aee23d174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017215" w-serial-number="2033807525" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1830bc3274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Mowoe v. State, 328 Ga. App. 536, 759 S.E.2d 663 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 10:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
